<td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/red_05.gif" class="headerbg"><font class="h1font"><font color="#FFFFFF"><table cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 border=0 width=100%><TR><td><font class="h1font">Articles</td><form method='post' action=''><input type="hidden" name="PHPSESSID" value="...328fedb22570524062aeb1303" /><td align='right' valign='bottom'><select name='select' onChange='go(this)'><option selected>More DeckTech Articles</option><option value='#'> </option><option value='/starwarsccg/articles/index.php3'>Star Wars: CCG</option><option value='/vs/articles/index.php3'>Marvel VS</option><option value='/heroclix/articles/articles.php'>HeroClix</option><option value='/lotr/articles/articles.php'>Lord of the Rings</option><option value='/magination/articles/articles.php'>Magi-Nation Duel</option><option value='/swtcg/articles/articles.php'>Ophidian 2350</option><option value='/magic/treports/treports.php'>The Wastelands</option></select></td></form></tr></table></font></B></td><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/red_06.gif"></td></tr>
	<tr><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_07.gif"></td>
		<td bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_08.gif"><font class="bfont"><font class="h1font"> Deckbuilding : The Fun and The Work<br></font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Overall Rating:</b> </font><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><font size='1'>(4.43)</font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Author:</b> <A HREF='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=15932'>Olivier "Mas3rTech" De Ridder</A></font><font class="afont"> <a href='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=15932&sub=1'> (Subscribe to this member)</a><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Date Submitted:</b> April 8, 2004</font><p align='justify'><font class="bfont"> Hello all ,<br />
<br />
I would like to split this article in different parts.<br />
<br />
1.Your starting point :<br />
When wanting to build a deck , the first thing I do is go to a local shop and meet with some friends.There we extensivly discuss the goods and the bads about a new set and what strategies could be very promissing.<br />
Before you go there , make sure you got some idea&#39;s yourself , you don&#39;t want to leach on other ppl&#39;s idea&#39;s and claim them your decks , while putting no energy in it yourself :].<br />
<br />
2.Decktech :<br />
Why is decktech so important in order to make a good deck?<br />
Well first off , you go look there to see what ppl are playing , cse alot of big tournament winning decks are posted there , aswell of reports of big tours.There ppl often note what difficulty they had vs this or that deck and you can learn alot from reading those notes.<br />
It&#39;s nice to make a summary in a folder with your findings.<br />
For example you see alot of stoopid swarms are getting popular , so you will ask yourself the question :<br />
How will my deck be able to cope with this , or will I simply hope for the best vs that matchup and protect my deck against everything else?<br />
<br />
3.Finetune / Playtest / Finetune<br />
The most important part of your deckbuilding will be this stage.As you have found different counters for this and that deck and all want them in your deck and still have a nice frame to work with , you&#39;ll find your deck way too beefy to be actualy tournament worthy!<br />
It&#39;s often the best choise to make a realy solid fellowship that either focuses on big wounding pre-skirmish or on winning skirmishes and the ability to get rid of possesions , both with some swarm protection like Paths , curse their foul feet , sting , orc bane , there and back again , etc ... .<br />
When you have done this you try to find a way to make it either cycle realy nice and have about 32-33 cards in it , or less cycle with 30/30 decks.If your building a swarm , its recommended to have about 35+ cards in your deck , cse you run through it anyhow.<br />
<br />
Then you meet with some friends and start testing.<br />
At that stage you will often notice that how powerfull your deck might have looked in your list , it just doesn&#39;t give the result anticipated :/ . When you come accros these flaws , be happy ! It&#39;s way better to see that your deck has flaws at some points , rather then to find it out in a big tournament and going home with a loss streak .<br />
Take some notes either in your mind or on a paper and show your deck to your friends and ask them what they think can improve this deck.They will often make very good points that they have learned from their tournament exp. that could help your deck be even better.<br />
<br />
4.Post it on decktech :<br />
There are two options :<br />
Either the deck is so risky to play that you don&#39;t post it in fear that everyone will counter it , or if it&#39;s regular you do best to post it and be realy nice to the ppl.<br />
<br />
In alot of cases nice ppl  give VERY GOOD reviews , telling you whats their vision of this deck and what could be added to make it better.You don&#39;t need 5 players giving you 5 stars , who gives a ... about that anyhow?<br />
You need the one player Saying :<br />
Hey guy , i think a curse them could realy improve your deck , or : You haven&#39;t put any protection vs swarm in it.<br />
I suggest this or that . Even if you only get 3 stars but the review is correct you should be very happy !<br />
<br />
5.Go to a local tournament :<br />
<br />
After your deck is finished , try it in your local tournament and you will soon find out the lacking key ( if there is still one ) that can lead you to victory in a big tournament like a TOC/PSQ.<br />
<br />
<br />
So there it is , thnx for reading all.<br />
<br />
Cheerz<br />
Olivier De Ridder<br />
